&gt;As for communism. Yes there was a part of the movement that was communists. Communism has a tradition in the US that is a valid ideology, whether we like it or not. Again judge what people do, not what they think. Like most people communists did good things and bad things. They are people and not monsters, and yes they did believe that the war was wrong.&lt;<br><br>
I never knew anyone with the level of committment in the anti-war movement that you indicate you had.  I know that many people who protested the war were not communists, however, I don't know whether any of them, or how many of them knew that communists were part of the movement.  I know this question sounds simplistic after the above two posts.  Gotta ask to understand where you are coming from though.  Are/were you a communist during the time you were protesting the war?  How do you know that the communist believed that the war was wrong?  The next logical question is why did they believe it to be wrong?  <br><br>
In my mind, I cannot help but question whether the involvement of communists in the antiwar movement was an individual conscience issue or something much more calculated by the party to internally weaken the resolve of the American people .  
